The '''American Osteopathic Board of Orthopedic Surgery (AOBOS)''' is an organization that provides [[board certification]] to qualified [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine|Doctors of Osteopathic Medicine]] (D.O.) who specialize in the medical and surgical treatment of disorders of the [[musculoskeletal system]] ([[orthopedic surgeons]]). The board is one of 18 [[Specialty (medicine)| medical specialty]] certifying boards of the [[American Osteopathic Association Bureau of Osteopathic Specialists]] approved by the [[American Osteopathic Association]] (AOA),<ref>{{cite web|title=American Osteopathic Board of Orthopedic Surgery|url=http://www.hwic.org/experts/details.php?id=3121|year=2011|publisher=Health Workforce Information Center|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=AOA Specialty Certifying Boards|url=https://www.osteopathic.org/inside-aoa/development/aoa-board-certification/Pages/aoa-specialty-boards.aspx|publisher=American Osteopathic Association|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> and was originally a subdivision of the [[American Osteopathic Board of Surgery]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ayres|first=RE|coauthors=Scheinthal, S; Gross, C; Bell, EC|title=Osteopathic specialty board certification.|journal=The Journal of the American Osteopathic Association|year=2009|month=March|volume=109|issue=3|pages=181–90|pmid=19336771|url=http://www.jaoa.org/content/109/3/181.long|accessdate=13 September 2012}}</ref> until it became an independent board in 1978. As of December 2011, 1,082 [[Osteopathic medicine in the United States|osteopathic]] orthopedic surgeons held active certification with the AOBOS.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ayres|first=Ronald E|coauthors=S Scheinthal, C Gross, and E Bell.|title=Changes to Osteopathic Specialty Board Certification|journal=Journal of the American Osteopathic Association|year=2012|month=April|volume=112|issue=4|pages=226–231|url=http://www.jaoa.org/content/112/4/226.full.pdf+html|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Additionally, diplomates of the American Osteopathic Board of Orthopedic Surgery are eligible for membership in the [[American Society for Surgery of the Hand]]<ref name="Membership">{{cite web|url=http://www.assh.org/Professionals/AboutASSH/JoinASSH/Pages/default.aspx  |title=Join ASSH |author= |year=2013 |work= |publisher=American Society for Surgery of the Hand |accessdate=25 September 2012}} </ref> and the [[American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaos.org/member/mbrsvc/membership.asp|title=Membership Benefits and Information |author= |year=2013 |work= |publisher=American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons |accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref>
==Board certification==
To become board certified in orthopedic surgery, candidates must have completed an AOA-approved [[medical residency|residency]] in orthopedic surgery and one year of practice following the completion of residency. Additionally, candidates must have performed at least 200 major orthopedic surgeries in the year preceding application for board certification, and successfully completed the required clinical, oral, and written exams.<ref name="handbook">{{cite web |url=http://www.aobos.org/mm/files/Candidate-Handbook-Master.pdf |title=AOBOS 2012 Candidate Handbook |author= |year=2012 |work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Orthopedic Surgery |accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Since 1994, board certified osteopathic orthopedic surgeons must renew their certification every ten years to avoid expiration of their board certification status.<ref name="handbook"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aobos.org/content/104/recertification.aspx |title=Board Recertification |author= |year=2012 |work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Orthopedic Surgery |accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> 

Board certified osteopathic orthopedic surgeons may also receive Certification of Added Qualifications (CAQ) in [[Hand Surgery]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Specialties & Subspecialties|url=http://www.osteopathic.org/inside-aoa/development/aoa-board-certification/Pages/specialty-subspecialty-certification.aspx|publisher=American Osteopathic Association|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref><ref name="Hand">{{cite web |url=http://www.assh.org/Members/Maintenance/Pages/CAQSH.aspx |title=Subspecialty Certificate in Surgery of the Hand (formerly CAQ Hand) |author= |year=2013 |work= |publisher=American Society for Surgery of the Hand |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> Osteopathic orthopedic surgeons must renew their CAQ credentials every ten years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Medical Boards: Osteopathic|url=http://www.castleconnolly.com/resources/osteopathic.cfm|publisher=Castle Connolly Medical, Ltd.|year=2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref>

